# Set alias for convenience (optional)
alias kafka-docker="docker exec -it kafka kafka-topics.sh --bootstrap-server localhost:9092"
Or use this directly in commands:

bash
Copy
Edit
docker exec -it kafka <command>
‚úÖ 1. Create a Topic
bash
Copy
Edit
docker exec -it kafka \
  kafka-topics.sh --create \
  --topic my-topic \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 \
  --partitions 3 \
  --replication-factor 1
üìã 2. List Topics
bash
Copy
Edit
docker exec -it kafka \
  kafka-topics.sh --list \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092
üîç 3. Describe Topic (see partitions, leader, etc.)
bash
Copy
Edit
docker exec -it kafka \
  kafka-topics.sh --describe \
  --topic my-topic \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092
‚ùå 4. Delete a Topic
bash
Copy
Edit
docker exec -it kafka \
  kafka-topics.sh --delete \
  --topic my-topic \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092
‚ö†Ô∏è Deletion must be enabled in Kafka config:

yaml
Copy
Edit
delete.topic.enable=true
If using docker-compose, add this to your KAFKA_CFG_ env variables or server config.

üîÑ 5. Clear All Messages (Retain Topic, Drop Data)
There‚Äôs no direct "truncate" command in Kafka. But here are 2 workarounds:

üÖ∞Ô∏è Option A: Set retention to 0 (immediate cleanup)
bash
Copy
Edit
docker exec -it kafka \
  kafka-configs.sh --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 \
  --entity-type topics --entity-name my-topic \
  --alter --add-config retention.ms=1000
Wait a few seconds, then restore it:

bash
Copy
Edit
docker exec -it kafka \
  kafka-configs.sh --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 \
  --entity-type topics --entity-name my-topic \
  --alter --delete-config retention.ms
üÖ±Ô∏è Option B: Delete and Recreate Topic (if allowed)
bash
Copy
Edit
# Delete topic
docker exec -it kafka \
  kafka-topics.sh --delete \
  --topic my-topic \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092

# Recreate it fresh
docker exec -it kafka \
  kafka-topics.sh --create \
  --topic my-topic \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 \
  --partitions 1 --replication-factor 1
üßπ 6. Clear a Specific Partition (manual method)
Kafka doesn‚Äôt let you "delete messages from a partition" directly ‚Äî but you can:

Use retention.ms or segment.ms configs per partition

Write a script to consume and delete manually (e.g., via compacted topic or consumer offset reset)

Manual Purge via Admin API (advanced): requires using Kafka Admin client in Java.

üéØ Bonus: Reset Consumer Group Offset (to "replay" messages)
bash
Copy
Edit
docker exec -it kafka \
  kafka-consumer-groups.sh \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 \
  --group my-consumer-group \
  --topic my-topic \
  --reset-offsets --to-earliest --execute


Send messages WITH header using Kafka Console Producer
bash
Copy
Edit
docker exec -it kafka \
  kafka-console-producer.sh \
  --broker-list localhost:9092 \
  --topic input-topic \
  --property "parse.key=true" \
  --property "key.separator=:" \
  --property "headers=status=completed"
Once it opens an interactive prompt, enter messages like:

text
Copy
Edit
myKey:This is a message with completed status
You can also set multiple headers like:

bash
Copy
Edit
--property "headers=status=completed,source=manual"
‚ùå 2. Send messages WITHOUT headers
Just omit the --property headers=...:

bash
Copy
Edit
docker exec -it kafka \
  kafka-console-producer.sh \
  --broker-list localhost:9092 \
  --topic input-topic \
  --property "parse.key=true" \
  --property "key.separator=:"
Enter:

pgsql
Copy
Edit
someKey:Hello without header
Or, even simpler (no key-value):

bash
Copy
Edit
docker exec -it kafka \
  kafka-console-producer.sh \
  --broker-list localhost:9092 \
  --topic input-topic
Then:

pgsql
Copy
Edit
Just some plain text message
üß™ 3. Send JSON messages (optional)
